04072nam a22005775i 9780822395706DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20152015ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015008870  a97808223957067 a10.1515/97808223957062doi  a(DE-B1597)552659  a(OCoLC)1224278664  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aF2651.S136bP4535 2015 4aF2651.S139bC72 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aCollins, John F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRevolt of the Saints :bMemory and Redemption in the Twilight of Brazilian Racial Democracy /cJohn F. Collins. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b57 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Being, through the Archive -- t1 "The Eighteenth Battalion of Love" -- t2 Letters to the Amazons -- t3 Prostitution's Bureaucracy -- t4 A Metaphysics for Our Time -- t5 Treasure Tales and National Bodies -- t6 "But Madame, What If I Should Need to Defecate in Your Neighborhood?" -- t7 "Chatty Chatty Mouth, You Want to Know Your Culture" -- tConclusion: Saints, Not Angels -- tAppendix: Acronyms Used -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1985 the Pelourinho neighborhood in Salvador, Brazil was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Over the next decades, over 4,000 residents who failed to meet the state's definition of "proper Afro-Brazilianness" were expelled to make way for hotels, boutiques, NGOs, and other attractions. In Revolt of the Saints, John F. Collins explores the contested removal of the inhabitants of Brazil's first capital and best-known site for Afro-Brazilian history, arguing that the neighborhood's most recent reconstruction, begun in 1992 and supposedly intended to celebrate the Pelourinho's working-class citizens and their culture, revolves around gendered and racialized forms of making Brazil modern. He situates this focus on national origins and the commodification of residents' most intimate practices within a longer history of government and elite attempts to "improve" the citizenry's racial stock even as these efforts take new form today. In this novel analysis of the overlaps of race, space, and history, Collins thus draws on state-citizen negotiations of everyday life to detail how residents' responses to the attempt to market Afro-Brazilian culture and reimagine the nation's foundations both illuminate and contribute to recent shifts in Brazil's racial politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aBlackszBrazilzSalvador. 0aPelourinho (Salvador, Brazil) - Race relations. 4aAnthony Leeds Prize winner. 4aSUNTA prize. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395706zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395706.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles